  <dt id="1_01">
    I want to do the most to help other people, but I don’t think that
    professional philanthropy is the best way to go about it.  Can I still
    join?
  </dt>
  <dd>
    <p>
    Though we often introduce the High Impact Careers concept with the example of
    a professional philanthropist, we acknowledge that there are a variety of
    plausible career paths through which one can have a huge impact.  In
    particular, it’s very plausible that certain careers which give one influence
    and certain research careers can also be extremely high impact.
    For many people, they can be a better way to help other people than
    professional philanthropy.
    </p>
    <p>
    For some people, in fact, working in the charity sector really is the best
    thing they can do.  This can be true, for example, if you have a rare
    particular skill that you can add to a very cost-effective charity.  We warmly
    welcome such people into the High Impact community.
    </p>

<a href="#page_container">back to top</a>
</dd>



<dt id="1_02">
Why do you think that some causes are so much better than others?
</dt>

<dd>
<p>
The organisation <a href="http://www.givingwhatwecan.org/">Giving What We Can</a> has drawn on the latest cost-effectiveness research from health and development economics in order to work out which charities do the most to help other people with every pound or dollar they receive.  The results are remarkable: they have shown that our ability to help others depends dramatically on the way we choose to help them. 
</p>
<p>
For example, by funding cholera immunization in order to prevent diarrheal disease, one can give someone an additional year of healthy life for $2,945. This is certainly worth doing. But there is an opportunity cost. By funding hygiene education—a cheap but highly effective program—one can give almost 1000 people the same health benefit, again through prevention of diarrheal disease, for the same amount of money. By choosing the right cause, we can achieve a truly stunning bang for the buck: we can do hundreds of times as much good as we might otherwise have done.  
</p>

<p>
Moreover, this variability in effectiveness is merely within interventions in the developing world; if one compares causes in the developed world and developing world, the discrepancy can be even greater.  
</p>
<p>
If one wants to help others, it’s extremely important that one chooses the right way to do it.
</p>
<p>
To read more about Giving What We Can’s research, please see: <a href="http://www.givingwhatwecan.org/resources/recommended-charities.php">givingwhatwecan.org/recommended-charities.php</a>
</p>
<a href="#page_container">back to top</a>
</dd>




<dt id="1_03">
Are you only concerned with global poverty?  What about other causes?
</dt>

<dd>
<p>
Though we often use global poverty as an example, High Impact Careers does not limit itself to any one particular cause or type of cause.  There are many plausibly high impact causes, and there is room for reasonable disagreement about which it is most important to pursue.  
</p>
<p>
A non-exhaustive list of such causes includes those tackling the problems of: global poverty; climate change; animal suffering; and global catastrophic risks, such as the proliferation of nuclear and biological weapons.
</p>
<a href="#page_container">back to top</a>
</dd>




