<dt id="1_06">
Won’t I burn out if I become a professional philanthropist?
</dt>

<dd>
<p>
Risk of burnout, whether through overwork or through not being happy in your work, is certainly an important consideration when considering which career to pursue.  If you’re thinking about pursuing a high impact career, you should think carefully about the risks of failing to follow through in your aims, and normally you should choose a career that you think you will be pretty happy in.
</p>

<p>
Moreover, there are ways to mitigate the burnout risk.  By joining a community of like-minded people, you may increase your sense of purpose in life, and so find your work more fulfilling.  Another option is to try out a certain career path for a couple of years; and if it’s too stressful or demanding, then one can pursue something else.
</p>
<a href="#page_container">back to top</a>
</dd>



<dt id="1_07">
Won’t I get corrupted if I become a professional philanthropist?
</dt>

<dd>
<p>
Risk of becoming corrupted and losing one’s ideals is also an important consideration when considering which career to pursue.  Similar considerations that were raised in relation to burning out also apply to the risk of becoming corrupted.
</p>
<a href="#page_container">back to top</a>
</dd>




<dt id="1_08">
Shouldn’t we be trying to change the system, instead of working within it?  So shouldn’t we become activists instead?
</dt>
<dd>
<p>
Many of our members think systemic change is incredibly important and would greatly prefer a world with a far more equal income distribution. However, it doesn’t follow that we should all become full-time activists. First, it may be even better to invest time in other causes. It's up for debate whether time spent advocating for systemic change is more effective than saving thousands of lives with charitable donations. Second, even if you believe political campaigning for systemic change is the most important cause, it may be better to pursue a lucrative career and use the proceeds to pay for several activists to dedicate themselves to campaigning on your behalf. This is a lively topic of debate in our community. </p>


<a href="#page_container">back to top</a>
</dd>




<dt id="1_09">
I don’t think that doing good can be quantified.
</dt>

<dd>
<p>
It’s certainly true that it’s extremely difficult to quantify how much one helps others in one’s actions.  But that doesn’t show it’s impossible.
</p>

<p>
One way of quantifying benefit is by using a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quality-adjusted_life_year">Quality-Adjusted Life Year</a> (QALY).  This is a metric that quantifies health benefit by taking survey data from the potential beneficiaries of a particular health intervention.  This data measures the preferences that people have between different diseases and disabilities.  It is the metric used by advisors to developing world governments, so that they can spend their scarce health resources in a way that benefits their people as much as possible.  It currently is the gold-standard metric within health economics for quantifying health benefit.
</p>
<a href="#page_container">back to top</a>
</dd>




<dt id="1_10">
Don’t some lucrative careers cause harm?
</dt>

<dd>
<p>
It’s certainly true that some lucrative careers cause harm.   We wouldn’t recommend that someone becomes a hit man or a drug dealer in order to donate the profits to good causes!
</p>
<p>
Importantly, however, not all lucrative careers cause harm.  There are normally a wide variety of lucrative careers open to you, and you are encouraged to pursue a career that you feel ethically comfortable with.
</p>
<a href="#page_container">back to top</a>
</dd>



<dt id="1_11">
If everyone became a professional philanthropist, wouldn’t that mean that there were no charity workers to fund?
</dt>
<dd>
<p>
This is very true!  If we were getting to the point  where a large proportion of people were becoming professional philanthropists, then we would alter our recommendations about which career one ought to pursue. 
</p>

<p>
If only we were that persuasive!  Unfortunately, in the real world, most people aren’t intending to become professional philanthropists.  In general, graduates are far more willing to help a certain cause by working or volunteering in aid of that cause, than by donating money to that cause.  That’s why there’s currently such high ethical leverage to be gained by becoming a professional philanthropist, or by pursuing other high impact careers.
</p>
<a href="#page_container">back to top</a>
</dd>

